# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1968-tour-de-france
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The **1903 Tour de France** was the first cycling race set up and sponsored by the newspaper **L'Auto**, ancestor of the current daily, **L'Équipe**.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] It ran from 1 to 19 July in six stages over 2,428 km (1,509 mi), and was won by Maurice Garin.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The race was invented to boost the circulation of **L'Auto**, after its circulation started to plummet from competition with the long-standing **Le Vélo**.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Originally scheduled to start in June, the race was postponed one month, and the prize money was increased, after a disappointing level of applications from competitors.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The 1903 Tour de France was the first stage road race, and compared to modern Grand Tours, it had relatively few stages, but each was much longer than those raced today.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The cyclists did not have to compete in all six stages, although this was necessary to qualify for the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The pre-race favourite, Maurice Garin, won the first stage, and retained the lead throughout.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] He also won the last two stages, and had a margin of almost three hours over the next cyclist.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The circulation of **L'Auto** increased more than sixfold during and after the race, so the race was considered successful enough to be rerun in 1904, by which time **Le Vélo** had been forced out of business.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] After the Dreyfus affair separated advertisers from the newspaper **Le Vélo**, a new newspaper **L'Auto-Vélo** was founded in 1900, with former cyclist Henri Desgrange as editor.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] After being forced to change the name of the newspaper to **L'Auto** in 1903, Desgrange needed something to keep the cycling fans; with circulation at 20,000, he could not afford to lose them.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] When Desgrange and young employee Géo Lefèvre were returning from the Marseille–Paris cycling race, Lefèvre suggested holding a race around France, similar to the popular six-day races on the track.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Desgrange proposed the idea to the financial controller Victor Goddet, who gave his approval, and on 19 January 1903, the Tour de France was announced in **L'Auto**.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] It was to have been a five-week race, from 1 June to 5 July, with an entry fee of 20 francs.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] These conditions attracted very few cyclists: one week before the race was due to start, only 15 competitors had signed up.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Desgrange then rescheduled the race from 1 to 19 July, increased the total prize money to 20,000 francs, reduced the entry fee to 10 francs and guaranteed at least five francs a day to the first 50 cyclists in the classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] After that, 79 cyclists signed up for the race, of whom 60 actually started the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Géo Lefévre became the director, judge and time-keeper; Henri Desgrange was the *directeur-général*, although he did not follow the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The 1903 Tour de France was run in six stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The cyclists were not grouped in teams but raced as individuals, and paid a fee of ten francs (about €135 at 2023 prices) to compete in the race for general classification, or five francs to enter a single stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] As the stages were so long, all but the first started before dawn: the last stage started at 21:00 the night before.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The first Tour de France crossed no mountain passes, but several lesser cols.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The first was the col du Pin-Bouchain (759 m (2,490 ft)), on the opening stage from Paris to Lyon, on what is now the old road from Roanne to Lyon.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The stage from Lyon to Marseille included the col de la République (1,161 m (3,809 ft)), also known as the col de Grand Bois, at the edge of St-Etienne.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] In 1903, it was normal for a professional cyclist to hire pacers, who would lead them during the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Desgrange forbade this: it was originally intended that in the final, longest, stage pacers would be allowed, but this was rescinded after the fifth stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] To ensure that the cyclists rode the entire route, stewards were stationed at various points around the course.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The yellow jersey for the leader in the general classification had not yet been introduced, but the leader was identified by a green armband.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The fastest eight cyclists on each stage received a prize between 50 francs and 1,500 francs, varying per stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The fourteen best cyclists in the general classification received a prize from 3,000 francs for the winner to 25 francs for fourteenth place.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The remaining seven cyclists to finish in the general classification each received 95 francs, 5 francs for each of the 19 days that the race took, provided that they had not won more than 200 francs in prize money and did not have an average speed below 20 km/h (12 mph) on any stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] In contrast to modern stage races, a cyclist who gave up during a stage was allowed to start again the next stage, although he would no longer be in contention for the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Thus Hippolyte Aucouturier, who gave up during the first stage, was able to return, and won the second and third stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Charles Laeser, winner of the fourth stage, had not completed the third stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Sixty cyclists, all professionals or semi-professionals, started the race, of whom 49 were French, 4 Belgian, 4 Swiss, 2 German, and one Italian; 21 of them were sponsored by bicycle manufacturers, while 39 entered without commercial support.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] 24 other cyclists took advantage of the opportunity to enter specific stages: one rode in both the second and fourth stages, and additionally three cyclists took part in the second stage, one in the third stage, fifteen in the fourth stage only, and a further four only competed in the fifth stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The pre-race favourites for the victory were Maurice Garin and Hippolyte Aucouturier.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Garin dominated the race from the start by winning the first stage, a 471 km (293 mi) parcours from Paris to Lyon.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The stage started at 15:16, and the cyclists initially rode with a speed of 35 km/h.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The first cyclists abandoned after around 50 km (31 mi).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] At 23:00, Garin and Emile Pagie, leading the race, reached the control point in Nevers.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Garin expected at that point that they would finish at 8:00 the next morning.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] During the night, Garin's main rival, Aucouturier, had stomach cramps, and was unable to finish the stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Also during that first stage, the first breach of the rules occurred: Jean Fischer had used a car as pacer, which was illegal.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Pagie fell down, but got up again; he and Garin kept leading the race during the night.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Around 9:00 in the morning, both reached Lyon.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Garin got away from Pagie, and finished one minute ahead.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Although Aucouturier had abandoned in the first stage, and so was not eligible for the general classification, he could still start the rest of the stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] In the second stage, Aucouturier was able to win the sprint.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] In the third stage, the cyclists who were competing for the general classification started one hour earlier than the other cyclists, including Aucouturier.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] At the end of that stage, a group of four cyclists had broken away, and Eugène Brange won the sprint.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Aucouturier finished 27 minutes later, but this meant that he had run the course 33 minutes faster, so he was declared the winner of the stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Garin retained the lead, helped by a crash of second-placed Pagie in the second stage, which eliminated him from the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] In the fourth stage, Aucouturier had a clear lead and seemed set to win a third successive stage, but was caught using the slipstream of a car, and was removed from the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Swiss Charles Laeser (who had abandoned in the 3rd stage) took the victory, becoming the first non-French winner.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] As in the third stage, the cyclists departed in two groups, and Laeser was in the second group because he was no longer contending for the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Laeser finished more than 50 minutes after a group of six cyclists, but he had travelled the distance 4 minutes faster than them, so he was declared the winner.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] At that point, Garin was leading, with Émile Georget almost two hours behind.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] In the fifth stage, Georget had two flat tires, and fell asleep when he stopped at the side of the road to rest; he failed to finish.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Thus Garin extended his lead by winning this stage, carrying nearly three hours' advantage into the final day's racing.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Garin had requested other cyclists in the leading group to let him win the stage, but Fernand Augereau refused to do this.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Garin then had Lucien Pothier throw down his bicycle in front of Augereau, who fell, and Garin then bent Augereau's rear wheel.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Augereau quickly obtained a spare bike and continued to the finish, however Garin easily won the sprint.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Augereau still received a prize of 100 francs from Velo-Sport Nantes for the fastest final kilometre of the stage in the Nantes velodrome.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The last stage was the longest, at 471 km (293 mi), and ran from Nantes to the small town of Ville-d'Avray, which lies between Versailles and Paris, instead of at the Parc des Princes velodrome.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] This was because of a bylaw forbidding road races to end on cycling tracks (a bylaw subsequently repealed in light of the race's success).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Garin took his third stage win, and sealed overall victory by 2 hours 59 minutes 31 seconds: this remains the greatest margin of victory in the Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] After arriving at Ville-d'Avray the riders were given a board marked with their finishing time and cycled on to Parc des Princes where they made several laps of honour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] That day, 19 July, saw a large crowd at the velodrome to watch the riders and an earlier 100-km cycle race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] In 1903, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate whether the stage included mountains.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] There were 21 cyclists who had completed all six stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] For these cyclists, the times taken for each stage were added up for the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the winner.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The circulation of **L'Auto** increased significantly due to this event; a special edition of 130,000 copies was made after the race was over, and normal circulation increased from 25,000 to 65,000.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The big success made sure that the Tour de France was scheduled again for 1904.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] The cyclists had also become national heroes.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] Maurice Garin returned for the 1904 Tour de France but his title defence failed when he was disqualified.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1903-tour-de-france] With the prize money that he won in 1903, which totalled 6,075 francs, (approximately US$40,000 and GBP£23,000 in 2006 values) Garin later bought a gas station, where he worked for the rest of his life.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The **1904 Tour de France** was the second Tour de France, held from 2 to 24 July.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] With a route similar to its previous edition, 1903 Tour de France winner Maurice Garin seemed to have repeated his win by a small margin over Lucien Pothier, while Hippolyte Aucouturier won four of the six stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] But the race became a victim of its own success, plagued by scandals; cyclists were accused of having taken trains during the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Twelve cyclists, including the first four of the final classification and all stage winners, were disqualified by the Union Vélocipédique Française (UVF).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Henri Cornet, originally the fifth-place finisher, was awarded the victory four months after the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The problems caused the Tour de France to be provisionally cancelled, and subsequently the 1905 Tour de France was run with different rules from the 1903 and 1904 editions.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The initial Tour de France of 1903 had been a large success, and it was quickly decided to organise it again in 1904.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The route was identical, with the same six stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The rules were the same as in 1903, with one exception: cyclists could not enter in just one stage, but had to join for the entire race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The favourites for the victory were Garin, Pothier and Aucouturier, who had performed well in the 1903 Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Among the competitors was Henri Paret who, at 50 years old, still holds the record of oldest Tour de France cyclist.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In the 1903 Tour de France, the organisation guaranteed that the first 50 cyclists in the final general classification would earn at least 5 francs per day.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In 1904, if not more than 50 cyclists would finish, also cyclists who dropped out during the race would still get 5 francs for the days they had been in the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] This rule was added to attract cyclists who otherwise would not enter, because the Tour needed enough competitors to remain credible.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In the first stage, the riders fell after only a few kilometres.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Lipman broke a finger, and became the first rider to abandon this Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Around 100 km in the race, Lucien Pothier lost ten minutes to the main group, led by Maurice Garin, because of a broken bicycle.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In Cosne, at 174 km, Pothier had reached the leading group.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Aucouturier had lost more than one hour at that point.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Just before the next control post in Nevers, Aucouturier fell on his face, and continued the race covered in blood.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In the last part of the race, Maurice Garin and Lucien Pothier rode away from the others.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] They were attacked by four masked men in a car, but still finished as the first two, with Garin beating Pothier by 50 m.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The many flat tires and crashes of Aucouturier, seemingly the results of sabotage, gave him a time loss of several hours.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] After the stage, three cyclists were punished: Aucouturier and Samson received fines of 500 and 250 francs, Aucouturier for having a cyclist not in the race following him, Samson for riding in the slipstream of a car.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Chevallier, who had finished third, was disqualified for resting in a car for 45 minutes.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] During the stage, Ferdinand Payan had been disqualified.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Some sources indicate he was helped by a motor, others that he was helped by riders not in the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In that first stage, Garin had asked the race official Lefèvre for food, which was illegal.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Lefèvre, who knew that Garin was the star of the race, broke the rules and gave him the food, because he did not want to be responsible for Garin leaving the race because of hunger.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The news that Garin had received illegal help quickly spread, and caused the fanatical crowd to take action.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] For the second stage, the organisers had made the option to postpone the start by two hours, in case the mistral wind was making cycling difficult.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] This was not necessary, so the riders started at midnight as planned.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] During this stage, Antoine Fauré led close to his hometown, and 200 fans tried to stop the rest of the cyclists from following him.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Garin hurt his hand during the incident, and Giovanni Gerbi was knocked unconscious, and had to give up with broken fingers.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The situation was only solved after race officials fired shots in the air.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Further on, nails and broken glass had been spread along the road, which caused many flat tires.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Because of this help, Fauré was the first on top of the Col de la République, but was taken over by the favourites later.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] When the riders reached Marseille, they complained that there had been too many incidents in this stage, and the stage results should be cancelled.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In the last part, they had been stopped by a large group of cyclists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Maurice Garin had been attacked, and his arm had been injured: he finished the stage steering with only one hand.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] There was so much confusion at the last controle post, that the exact arrival times of the cyclists were not recorded.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In the third stage, the Tour reached Nîmes, near the home town of Payan, whose fans were angry because of his disqualification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] They threw rocks at the riders, and barricaded the road.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The cyclists had troubles passing through Nîmes, and several were injured.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The most important event for the general classification was when César Garin's bicycle was broken by attackers; he had to find a new bicycle, which took him 15 minutes.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Further on, nails and broken glass were spread along the road.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Many riders punctured, but there were no serious falls.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] After Nîmes, a leading group of five cyclists was formed: Maurice Garin, Pothier, Aucouturier, Cornet and Beaugendre.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Aucouturier and Cornet escaped, and Aucouturier won, beating Cornet in the sprint.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The fourth stage was run without the incidents that plagued the first three stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Pothier, Maurice and César Garin and Beaugendre reached Bordeaux together, and the stage was decided by the final kilometre in the velodrome, where Pothier recorded the fastest time.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In the fifth stage, nails on the road again causing punctures.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] As mechanical assistance was not allowed, Cornet had to ride the last 40 km on two flat tires.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Aucouturier won this stage, his third one, but was way behind in the general classification, which Garin led, with only 28 seconds margin to Pothier.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] In the sixth stage, Aucouturier, Garin and Dortignac escaped in the last kilometres.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Aucouturier signed first at the control post in Ville-d'Avray.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] From that point, the race was neutralised until the velodrome Parc-des-Princes, where the riders would ride the final kilometre.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] At the moment that the riders arrived in Paris, it started to rain.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The organisers decided together with the cyclists to exclude the final kilometre from the race, and make the control post in Ville-d'Avray the end of the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] This made Aucouturier the winner of the stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Maurice Garin finished second, which made him the overall winner.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Initially, Maurice Garin was declared the winner, having led the race from start to end.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] For each cyclist, the times they had needed in each stage was added up for the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the least accumulated time after the last stage was the winner.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] During the race, nine riders were excluded because of, among other actions, illegal use of cars or trains.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The Tour organisers were happy with the result, but the Union Vélocipédique Française (UVF) started an investigation after complaints from other cyclists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Their investigative committee heard testimony from dozens of competitors and witnesses, and, in December 1904, disqualified all the stage winners and the first four finishers (Maurice Garin, Pothier, César Garin, and Aucouturier).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Ten of those disqualified were banned for one year, Maurice Garin for two years and the remaining two for life.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The reasons for the disqualification were never made public.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Fifth-placed Henri Cornet, aged 19, then became the youngest ever winner of the Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Cornet had also been warned after he had received a lift by a car.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Only 15 cyclists from the original 27 that finished were not disqualified.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Following the disqualifications, the Tour de France came nearest in history to being permanently cancelled.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] The race organiser Henri Desgrange, said he would never run the race again because it had been overtaken by the "blind emotions" of those who attacked or helped riders as they passed.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Desgrange was also upset that the UVF had imposed judgement on his race when he had already disciplined riders as he saw fit.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] An angry exchange ensued between Desgrange and the UVF but the letters and the detailed complaints that led to the UVF's actions were lost when the Tour de France archives were transported south in 1940 to avoid the German invasion and were never seen again.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Until the end of his life, Garin always said that he was the rightful winner of the 1904 Tour de France, but according to Les Woodland, Garin confessed to a friend that he had cheated.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] After the disqualifications, the first four cyclists of the initial classification were disqualified.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Because of the scandals associated with this Tour, Desgrange wanted to stop the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] He however changed his mind, and the rules were changed to prevent cyclists from cheating: the 1905 Tour de France would be decided with a points system.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1904-tour-de-france] Tour de France 1904 winner Cornet would enter the Tour de France for seven more times, but would never again play an important role.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The **1905 Tour de France** was the third edition of the Tour de France, held from 9 to 30 July, organised by the newspaper *L'Auto*.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Following the disqualifications after the 1904 Tour de France, there were changes in the rules, the most important one being the general classification not made by time but by points.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The race saw the introduction of mountains in the Tour de France, and René Pottier excelled in the first mountain, although he could not finish the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Due in part to some of the rule changes, the 1905 Tour de France had less cheating and sabotage than in previous years, though they were not eliminated.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] It was won by Louis Trousselier, who also won four of the eleven stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] After the 1904 Tour de France, some cyclists were disqualified, most notably the top four cyclists of the original overall classification, Maurice Garin, Lucien Pothier, César Garin and Hippolyte Aucouturier.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Maurice Garin was originally banned for two years and Pothier for life, so they were ineligible to start the 1905 Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Of these four, only Aucouturier (who had been "warned" and had a "reprimand inflicted" on him), started the 1905 Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] They were disqualified by the Union Vélocipédique Française, based on accusations of cheating when there were no race officials around.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In 1904 Tour, it was difficult to observe the cyclists continuously, as significant portions of the race were run overnight, and the long stages made it difficult to have officials everywhere.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The first cyclist to cross the finish line received 1 point.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Other cyclists received one point more than the cyclist who passed the line directly before him, plus an additional point for every five minutes between them, with a maximum of ten points.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In this way, a cyclist could not get more than 11 points more than the cyclist that crossed the finish line just before him.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The other important introduction were the mountains.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] One of Desgrange's staffers, Alphonse Steinès, took Desgrange for a trip over the Col Bayard at 1,246 metres (4,088 ft) and the Ballon d'Alsace at 1,178 metres (3,865 ft), that had an average gradient of 5.2% with 10% at some places, to convince Desgrange to use these climbs in the route.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Desgrange accepted it, saying that Steinès would take the blame if the mountains would be too hard to climb.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In the two previous editions, the highest point was the Col de la République at 1,145 metres (3,757 ft).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In 1905, Desgrange chose to overlook this, and focused instead on the introduction of the Ballon d'Alsace, because he saw that he had missed the opportunity for publicity previously.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] There were two categories of riders, the *coureurs de vitesse* and the *coureurs sur machines poinçonnées*.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The riders in the first category were allowed to change bicycles, which could be an advantage in the mountains, where they could use a bicycle with lower gears.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The riders in the machines poinçonnées category had to use the same bicycle in the entire race, and to verify this, their bicycles were marked.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Before the race started, 77 riders had signed up for the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Seventeen of those did not start the race, so the Tour began with 60 riders, including former winner Henri Cornet and future winners René Pottier and Lucien Petit-Breton.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The riders were not grouped in teams, but most of them rode with an individual sponsor.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Two of the cyclists—Catteau and Lootens—were Belgian, all other cyclists were French.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Leading up to the start of the Tour, Wattelier, Trousselier, Pottier and Augereau were all considered the most likely contenders to win the event.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Despite the rule changes, there were still protesters among the spectators; in the first stage all riders except Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq punctured due to 125 kg of nails spread along the road.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The first stage was won by Louis Trousselier.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Trousselier was serving in the army, and had requested from his commander leave for the Tour de France; this was allowed for 24 hours.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] After he won the first stage and led the classification, his leave was extended until the end of the Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] From 60 starting cyclists, only 15 cyclists reached the finish line within the time limit; 15 more reached the finish after the limit and the rest took the train.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The Tour organiser Desgrange wanted to stop the race, but was persuaded by the cyclists not to do so, and allowed all cyclists to continue with 75 points.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In the second stage, the first major climb, the Ballon d'Alsace, made its debut.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Four riders were the fastest climbers: Trousselier, René Pottier, Cornet and Aucouturier.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Of those four, Trousselier and Aucouturier were the first to be dropped, and Cornet had to drop in the final kilometers.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The top was therefore reached first by René Pottier, without dismounting, at an average speed of 20 km/h.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Cornet, who reached the top second, had to wait 20 minutes for his bicycle with higher gear, because his support car had broken down.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Later Aucouturier caught Pottier, and dropped him, and won the stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Pottier became second in the stage and led the classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Seven cyclists did not reach the finish in time, but they were again allowed to start the next stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In the third stage, Pottier had to abandon due to tendinitis.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The lead was back with Trousselier, who also won the stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In the fourth stage, the Côte de Laffrey and the Col Bayard were climbed, the second and third mountains of the Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Julien Maitron reached both tops first, but Aucouturier won the stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Trousselier finished in second place, still leading the overall classification, although with the same number of points as Aucouturier.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In the fifth stage, Trousselier won, and because Aucouturier finished in twelfth place, Trousselier had a big lead in the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] After the fifth stage, Aucouturier could no longer challenge Trousselier for the lead.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In the seventh stage to Bordeaux, Trousselier punctured after only a few kilometers.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The rest of the cyclists quickly sped away from him, and Trousselier had to follow them alone for 200 km.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] A few kilometers before Bordeaux, Trousselier caught up with the rest, and even managed to win the sprint.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Louis Trousselier kept his lead until the end of the race, winning five stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Trousselier was accused of bad sportsmanship: he reportedly smashed the inkstands of a control post to prevent his opponents from signing.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Unlike the 1904 Tour de France, no stage winners, nor anyone from the top ten of the general classification, were disqualified.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In the first and last stage, the cyclists were allowed to use pacers.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The cyclists officially were not grouped in teams; some cyclists had the same sponsor, even though they were not allowed to work together.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] Pautrat was the winner of the *coureurs sur machines poinçonnées* category, having used the same bicycle through the whole event.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The organising newspaper L'Auto named René Pottier the *meilleur grimpeur*.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] This unofficial title is the precursor to the mountains classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The tour organisers liked the effect of the points system, and it remained active until the 1912 Tour de France, after which it was reverted to the time system.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In 1953, for the 50-years anniversary of the Tour de France, the points system was reintroduced as the points classification, and the winner was given a green jersey.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] This points classification has been active ever since.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The introduction of mountains in the Tour de France had also been successful.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] After the introduction of the Vosges in the 1905 Tour de France, in 1906 the Massif Central were climbed, followed by the Pyrenees in 1910 and the Alps in 1911.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The winner Trousselier received 6950 Francs for his victory.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The night after he won, he drank and gambled with friends, and lost all the money.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] In later years, Trousselier would not win a Tour de France again, but he still won eight more stages and finished on the podium in the next year.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] The unofficial mountain champion of the 1905 Tour de France, Pottier, would be more successful in the next year, when he won the overall classification and five stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1905-tour-de-france] For L'Auto, the newspaper that organised the Tour de France, the race was a success; the circulation had increased to 100,000.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The **1906 Tour de France** was the fourth edition of the Tour de France, and the second to use the points system.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Taking place from 4 to 29 July, the total race distance was 4,637 kilometres (2,881 mi) run over 13 stages, with the winner averaging 24.463 kilometres per hour (15.201 mph).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] New to this year's edition were the mountain climbs in the Massif Central.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] However, like its predecessors, cheating and sabotage still took place.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Four competitors were disqualified for taking trains as a shortcut and spectators threw nails on the road.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] However, this did not stop René Pottier from taking a big lead in the first stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Free of the tendinitis that had plagued his 1905 chances, he dominated the entire race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Tour organiser Henri Desgrange had been happy with the increased length of the 1905 Tour de France, and decided to put even more stages in the 1906 version.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The introduction of mountain stages had also been successful, so this edition included not only the Vosges, but also the Massif Central.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The increased length made it possible to follow the borders of France, and in 1906 the perimeter was closely followed.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The winner of the stage received one point, the second rider two points, et cetera.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] After the eighth stage, only 16 cyclists were remaining, and the results from the first eight stages were recalculated, with only the remaining cyclists, and the points were redistributed among the remaining riders in accordance with their positions in those stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The first stage ended in Lille and the second stage started in Douai; this was the first time that a stage did not start where the previous stage ended.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] And, for the first time, the Tour also went outside France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The second stage crossed the border into Germany (Metz in Alsace-Lorraine, then part of Germany), and several days later riders visited Italy (Ventimiglia) and Spain (Irun).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The 1906 Tour also saw the introduction of the *flamme rouge* (red flame), a red flag that indicates that the cyclists only have one kilometre to go.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] There were 100 cyclists signed up for the race, but only 76 of them came to the start.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] One of the absentees was Henri Cornet, winner of the 1904 Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Four cyclists were Belgian, one was Luxembourgian (later winner François Faber), two were German, and the rest were French.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Louis Trousselier, winner of the 1905 Tour de France, was present.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The riders were not grouped in teams, but some cyclists had the same sponsor, even though they were not allowed to work together.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Before the race started, most was expected from Cadolle, Aucouturier, Georget, Pottier, Trousselier, Dortignac and Petit-Breton.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] As in 1905, the cyclists were divided in two categories, the *coureurs de vitesse* and the *coureurs sur machines poinçonnées*, where the riders in the first category were allowed to change bicycles, which could be an advantage in the mountains, where they could use a bicycle with lower gears.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] In 1905, sponsors had not been so enthusiastic about entering their cyclists in this category, but in 1906 they had learned that it had a commercial advantage to have cyclists starting in the poinçonnées category, because the average French citizen could identify more with them.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] In 1906, more than half of the cyclists started in the poinçonnées category, including Lucien Petit-Breton, one of the pre-favourites.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] As in previous years, the spectators tried to assist their preferred riders by trying to impede their opponents.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] On the first stage, nails had been thrown on the road, and all cyclists except Lucien Petit-Breton punctured.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] This stage was won by Emile Georget in a sprint.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] In the second stage, René Pottier, who had shown his climbing abilities in the previous edition, aimed for the victory.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] He was stopped after 175 kilometres (109 mi) with mechanical failure, and he lost 58 minutes.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The other main contenders worked together to stay away from Pottier, but Pottier chased them for 200 kilometres (120 mi), caught them 25 kilometres (16 mi) before the finish, and even left them behind, winning the stage with a margin of 1'30" on Petit-Breton and more than 9 minutes on the rest.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] In the third stage, four cyclists (Julien Gabory, Henri Gauban, Gaston Tuvache and Maurice Carrere) were disqualified for taking the train.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The Ballon d'Alsace, which had been the first real mountain in the Tour de France the previous year, was featured again.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Just as the year before, it was mounted first by Pottier.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The stage was also won by Pottier, more than 45 minutes ahead of the rest.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] In the fifth stage, he was leading by one hour at the halfway point.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] A cycling legend says that he decided to stop, entered a bar and ordered a bottle of wine, and drank it almost completely.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] When he saw the first other cyclists passing by, Pottier mounted his bicycle again, went after them, and won the stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] By this point, Pottier was leading the overall classification firmly.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The winner of the 1905 Tour de France, Louis Trousselier, had had a bad first half of the Tour, and was many points behind.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Trousselier rediscovered his form in the second half of the race, won the 7th, 9th, 10th and 11th stages, and was challenging the second place of Georges Passerieu.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Passerieu defended his position by winning the 12th stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] In the last stage, Pottier showed his strength by winning the stage, after finishing together in Paris with Passerieu.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] After the 13th stage, the race was followed by two timed exhibition laps on the Velodrome in Paris, the result of which was not counted for the overall classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The winner was Emile Georget, who finished the 1,332 metres (4,370 ft) in 2:07.20.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] One hundred cyclists had entered for the 1906 Tour de France; only 82 of them showed up at the start.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Only 49 cyclists finished the first stage, and the number of active cyclists quickly fell to 37 in stage two, 29 in stage three, until 16 after stage eight.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] At that point, the points given in the first eight stages were redistributed among the remaining riders in accordance with their positions in those stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] At the end of the Tour de France, only 14 cyclists finished.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The cyclists were not grouped in teams; some cyclists had the same sponsor, but they were not allowed to work together.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Lucien Petit-Breton was the winner of the "machines poinçonnées" category.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The Tour organisers did not make many changes the rules or route for the next race, because they had worked in the 1906 Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The revised points system would be kept in this form until 1911, only to be changed a little bit in 1912 before being replaced by the time system in 1913.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] The flamme rouge that was introduced in 1906 to indicate the final kilometre of a stage was kept and is still in use.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] René Pottier would not defend his title in the 1907 Tour de France, because he would commit suicide before, after discovering that his wife had had an affair while he was riding the Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton and Georget would start again in the 1907 Tour and duel for the overall victory, which would be won by Petit-Breton.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1906-tour-de-france] To honor Pottier's achievements on the Ballon d'Alsace, a monument was placed for him on top of that mountain.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The **1907 Tour de France** was the fifth running of the annual Tour de France, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] From 8 July to 4 August, the 93 cyclists cycled 4488 km (2,788 mi) in fourteen stages around France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The winner, Lucien Petit-Breton, completed the race at an average speed of 28.47 km/h (17.69 mph).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] For the first time, climbs in the Western Alps were included in the Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The race was dominated at the start by Émile Georget, who won five of the first eight stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] In the ninth stage, he borrowed a bicycle from a befriended rider after his own broke.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] This was against the rules; initially he received only a small penalty and his main competitors left the race out of protest.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Georget's penalty was then increased and Lucien Petit-Breton became the new leader.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton won two of the remaining stages and the overall victory of the Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The 1907 Tour de France incorporated 14 stages, which was one more than in 1906.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] For the first time, roads in Switzerland were included.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The mountain stages in 1906 had been so successful, according to the organiser Henri Desgrange, that the western Alps were included in the race for the first time.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The 1907 race was also the first time that a car with bicycle repairmen drove behind the riders, to give assistance in solving mechanical problems on bicycles.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] As in 1906, the race was decided by a points system.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] At the end of every stage, the winner was given one point, the next cyclist two points, and so on.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] After the eighth stage, when there were only 49 cyclists left in the race, the points given in the first eight stages were redistributed among the remaining cyclists, according to their positions in those stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] René Pottier, the winner of the 1906 Tour de France, did not defend his title because he had committed suicide in early 1907.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Although the riders officially rode the Tour as individuals, some shared the same sponsor and cooperated as if they rode in teams.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] At the start of the race, it was expected that the riders sponsored by Alcyon and the riders sponsored by Peugeot would compete for the overall victory.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Alcyon started with three main contenders: Louis Trousselier, Marcel Cadolle and Léon Georget; Peugeot counted on Emile Georget.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] As in the previous years, there were two classes of cyclists, the *coureurs de vitesse* and the *coureurs sur machines poinçonnées*.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Of the 93 cyclists starting the race, 82 were in the *poinçonnée* category, which meant that they had to finish the race on the same bicycle as they left, and if it was broken they had to fix it without assistance.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The *coureurs de vitesse* could get help from the car with bicycle repairmen when they had to fix a bicycle, and when a bicycle was beyond repair, they could change it to a new one.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Not all cyclists were competing for the victory; some only joined as tourists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The most notable of them was Henri Pépin.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Pépin had hired two riders, Jean Dargassies and Henri Gauban, to ride with him.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] They treated the race as a pleasure ride, stopping for lunch when they chose and spending the night in the best hotels they could find.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Dargassies and Gaubin became the first cyclists in the history of the Tour de France to ride not for their own placings but for another rider's interest.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] During the race, they found another Tour de France competitor, Jean-Marie Teychenne, lying in a ditch.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] They helped him get up and fed him; from then on Teychenne also helped Pépin.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Early in the race, Trousselier, François Faber and Emile Georget were the main contenders.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Trousselier, winner of the 1905 Tour de France and eager to win again, won the first stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] In the second stage, the Tour passed the French-German border to finish in Metz, which was then part of Germany.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The German authorities allowed the cyclists to finish there, but did not allow the French flag to be flown or the cars of race officials to enter the city.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] At the end of the stage, Emile Georget seemingly beat Trousselier with a very small margin.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] After inquiry, Desgrange, the Tour's organiser, decided to put both cyclists in first place, to keep both sponsors satisfied.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] In the third stage, the Tour returned to France; at the border, the riders were stopped by two French customs officers and the delay took so long that the stage had to be restarted.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] During the stage in the Alps, Émile Georget was better than his competitors; he won the stage and became leader of the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Georget won five of the first eight stages, and had a commanding lead.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] In the seventh stage, Marcel Cadolle, at that time in second place, fell and his handlebar penetrated his knee, after which he had to give up.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] During the ninth stage, when Georget was leading the race, he broke the frame of his bicycle at a checkpoint.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] According to the rules, Georget should have fixed his bicycle alone; he knew this would take him more than five hours, so he switched bicycles with Pierre-Gonzague Privat.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] This was against the rules, so Georget was given a fine of 500 francs.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Unsatisfied with the fine given to Georget, Trousselier and the other riders sponsored by Alcyon left the Tour in protest.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] After the tenth stage, the organisers gave Georget an additional penalty for the bicycle change in the ninth stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] They changed the classification of the ninth stage, moving Georget from 4th on the stage to last (48th place).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] This effectively cost him 44 points in the general classification and moved him from first to third place.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Lucien Petit-Breton became the new leader of the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Although he had already finished in fifth place and fourth place in previous years, he was still relatively unknown, and had started in the *coureurs sur machines poinçonnées* category.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton finished in the top three in the next stages, so no other cyclist was able to challenge him for the overall victory.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] At the end of the race, he had increased his lead to a margin of 19 points ahead of Garrigou and 27 points ahead of Georget.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] In the first and final stages, the cyclists were allowed to have pacers.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Although 110 riders were on the starting list, 17 did not show up, so the race started with 93 cyclists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] At the end of the Tour de France, 33 cyclists remained.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The total prize money was 25000 French francs, of which 4000 francs were given to Petit-Breton for winning the Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] In total, he received more than 7000 francs.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Lucien Petit-Breton was also the winner of the "machines poinçonnées" category.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] The organising newspaper l'Auto named Emile Georget the *meilleur grimpeur*.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] This unofficial title is the precursor to the modern-day mountains classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton also started the 1908 Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1907-tour-de-france] He won five stages and the general classification, and became the first cyclist to win the Tour de France two times.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The **1908 Tour de France** was the sixth running of the annual Tour de France, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] It was organised by the newspaper *L'Auto*, and took place between 13 July and 9 August.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The Tour was split in 14 stages, with a total distance of 4,497 kilometres (2,794 mi).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The pre-race favourite was Lucien Petit-Breton, winner of the previous Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton dominated the race; he won the general classification and five of the fourteen stages, and thus became the first cyclist who won the Tour twice.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] For the first time, the final podium in Paris was not completely French: François Faber from Luxembourg ended as second in the general classification, after winning four stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The 1908 Tour de France followed nearly the same route as the 1907 Tour de France, following the borders of France clockwise.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The rules were also the same; the points system was still used instead of the time system to determine the winner.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Before the start, the Tour de France organization announced that all necessary measures had been taken to prevent the regrettable incidents as in 1905, and that the 'Apaches' had 90% chance of being caught and spending time in jail.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Dismountable tyres were used for the first time; this meant that cyclists could repair their bicycles easier, and a flat tire cost them less time.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Because tour organiser Henri Desgrange wanted to keep the Tour de France a race between individual athletes, all cyclists had to ride on frames provided by the Tour organisation.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The cyclists were not allowed to change bicycles, so the separation in two different classes in the years before had disappeared, and all cyclists started in the same category.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Before the race started, 162 cyclists had subscribed for the Tour de France, and received starting numbers.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] 48 cyclists did not start, so the first stage started with 114 cyclists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Cyclists entered the race individually, not in teams; nevertheless some shared the same sponsor and cooperated as if they rode in teams.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The favourite for the victory was Lucien Petit-Breton, the winner of the previous edition.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] He was sponsored by Peugeot, which sponsored also several other strong cyclists; in the five previous editions of the Tour de France, these Peugeot-sponsored cyclists had together won 20 stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In addition, Petit-Breton was a skilled bicycle mechanic, which was important because the rules said that cyclists had to repair their bicycle without help.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The strongest opposition was expected from the cyclists sponsored by Alcyon, led by Georges Passerieu and Gustave Garrigou.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The Labor-sponsored cyclists started the race in yellow jerseys; in 1908 the yellow jersey for the race leader was not used yet.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] French athlete Marie Marvingt had tried to participate in the 1908 Tour de France, but was refused permission because the race was only open to men.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] She rode the route after the race, and managed to finish it.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] At one stage, Henri Desgrange's car broke down, and the tour organiser had to finish the stage in a horse-drawn carriage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In the first stage, from Paris to Roubaix, the cobbles caused many crashes and flat tyres.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] It was won by Georges Passerieu, while Petit-Breton finished second.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The second stage, from Roubaix to Metz, went through Alsace-Lorraine, which was in 1908 part of the German Empire.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] As in previous years, nails had been thrown on the road.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] This stage was won by Petit-Breton with Passerieu in second place.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Having both won a stage and finished second in the other, Petit-Breton and Passerieu both had 3 points.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Some sources show them joint leaders after that stage, while other sources show Passerieu as single leader.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In the third stage, started by Count Zeppelin, the Labor boss sent a telegram to the manager of the team after another crash by a Labor team member (Jean Novo): "After Novo's crash and the mediocre results of the other riders, I have decided to abandon the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] You can all ease up and come back by train." The rest of the Tour would be dominated by the cyclists from Peugeot, who won all the stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] At the third stage, Passerieu finished in 30th place; because Petit-Breton finished second, he was now leading the race by a big margin.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Faber had finished at 49th place in the second stage, so he was no direct threat for the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The fourth stage to Lyon was during a snow storm.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Faber won his second stage, and although he was still behind in the general classification, his two consecutive stage wins made him a dangerous competitor.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In the sixth stage, the Côte de Laffrey and the Col Bayard were climbed, and André Pottier, the younger brother of the 1906 Tour winner René Pottier, reached the tops first.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] He could not keep the lead, and Faber passed him.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Faber lost the lead when he had to stop to fix his bicycle, and at that point Giovanni Gerbi was in the lead.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] However, three kilometers before the finish, Gerbi's rear wheel broke; Gerbi could not quickly fix his bicycle, so he walked to the finish carrying his bicycle on his back, and finished in seventh place, while the stage was won by Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The seventh stage passed through Crau, in desert-like conditions.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton was best suited to this type of weather, and easily won.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In the ninth stage, won by Petit-Breton, Faber jumped to the second position in the overall classification, with 57 points, while Petit-Breton was still leading with 18 points.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton was at that moment almost guaranteed of the victory, because the remaining stages were all flat, which suited him well.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton crushed the other cyclists in the eleventh stage, dropping all other cyclists one by one.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In the remaining stages the other cyclists tried to beat Petit-Breton by escaping on turns, but Petit-Breton reeled them in each time.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In the 13th stage, 415 km from Brest to Caen, the winner Passerieu needed more than 16 hours to finish the stage; the last cyclist to finish that stage, Louis Di Maria, finished 23 hours after Passerieue.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Faber could pose no threat to Petit-Breton, and Petit-Breton won the Tour de France easily.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] His worst placement had been the 10th stage where he finished 10th at one second from the winner; all other stages he was in the top four, winning five of the stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] After the last stage, there was a timed lap of 666 m at the Parc des Princes velodrome in Paris, won by Henri Cornet in 51.2 s.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] This was not counted as an official stage and had no influence on the overall classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The general classification was calculated by points: at every stage, the winner was given one point, the next cyclist two points, etc.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] After the eighth stage, when only 39 cyclists were still in the race, the points given in the first eight stages were redistributed among the remaining cyclists, in accordance with their positions in those stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Of the 114 starting cyclists, 36 finished.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The Peugeot team had dominated the race; not only did their cyclists win all 14 stages, but they also had the top four places in the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Even though cyclists entered the race as individuals, officially not connected to sponsors, most cyclists had a sponsor.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] If the winner would have been determined by the time system as used in 1903 and 1904, Petit-Breton would also have been the winner, with Passerieu in second place, Garrigou in third and Faber in fourth.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Second-placed François Faber became the winner of the "pneus démontables" category.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The organising newspaper l'Auto named Gustave Garrigou the *meilleur grimpeur*.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In total, 25000 Francs were distributed in the 1908 Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The 1908 Tour was split into fourteen stages, and in all but the last stage, the best cyclists received prize money.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Between 400 and 500 French Francs was for the winner of each stage, down to 40 Francs for the seventh cyclist to finish.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] After the last stage, prizes were given for the position in the general classification: 5000 Francs for the winner, down to 100 Francs for the 25th place.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] All riders that finished were given at least 5 Francs per day.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] The winner Petit-Breton won 8050 Francs in this way; runner-up Faber won 4595 Francs.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] Lucien Petit-Breton became the first cyclist to win two Tours de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] He wrote a book about his life, "Comment je cours sur route".
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] This became a success, and he started to write cycling columns for newspapers.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1908-tour-de-france] In the next Tour in 1909, Petit-Breton did not participate as a cyclist, but followed the race as a columnist.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The **1909 Tour de France** was the seventh edition of the Tour de France, taking place from 5 July to 1 August.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] It consisted of 14 stages over 4,497 kilometres (2,794 mi), ridden at an average 28.658 km/h.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The results were computed by points accorded finishing positions on each stage, the rider with fewest points at the end of the race winning the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The stages were approximately the same as in the 1907 and 1908 Tour de France.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Because Lucien Petit-Breton, the winner of the Tour de France in 1907 and 1908, did not enter, the runner-up of 1908, François Faber, was the favourite.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Faber went on to win six of the 14 stages and won the race easily.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The 1909 Tour de France was again decided by the point system: the winner of a stage received one point, the second placed cyclist two points, and so on.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the fewest points at the end of the race was the winner.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] After the eighth stage, the classification was cleaned up, by removing the cyclists from the result of the previous stages and recalculating the points of the remaining cyclists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] This happened again after the thirteenth stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In 1908, the cyclists had to use Tour-supplied frames; this rule was abandoned in 1909.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The bicycles were still marked with a stamp, to ensure that the riders only used one bicycle.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] For the first time, cyclists could enter the race in teams, although technically they were still considered sponsored individuals.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In the previous Tours, the Tour organisation had become embarrassed by cyclists urinating in front of spectators, so at the check points obligatory bathrooms were installed.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The winner of the previous two editions, Lucien Petit-Breton, was not competing in 1909.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Petit-Breton expected his former teammate François Faber, who had become second in 1908, to win the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Faber had transferred from the Peugeot team, that had dominated the 1908 edition, to the Alcyon team.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] A new record of 150 cyclists started the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The previous Tours had been successful, and similar races were initiated in other countries (most notably the Tour of Belgium, which started in 1908 and the Giro d'Italia, which started in 1909).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The Tour de France was still the major race where the best cyclists came, and it was the first large-scale invasion of foreign stars.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In total, 19 Italians, 5 Belgians, 4 Swiss, 1 German and 1 Luxembourgian started the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Because cyclists could enter the race as sponsored cyclists, there were two classes of cyclists: cyclists with sponsors and cyclists without sponsors.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] There were seven different sponsors in the race (Nil–Supra, Alcyon, Biguet–Dunlop, Le Globe, Atala, Legnano and Felsina), with three to six cyclists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The majority of the cyclists, 112 in total, were not sponsored but were in the *Isolé* class, the class for cyclists without a sponsor.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The 1909 Tour de France was considered the most difficult one so far, because of the cold temperatures, the rain and snow.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The first stage was won by Belgian Cyrille van Hauwaert, the first Belgian stage victory ever.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] As a result, he was leading also the race, the first time in the Tour de France history that a non-Frenchman was leading the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] François Faber, the pre-race favourite, finished in second place.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] During that first stage, the weather had been reasonable, but at night the storm started.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Faber was best fit to those conditions, and he won the 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 5th and 6th stage, this record of five stages in a row has not been broken since.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In stage two, Faber broke away halfway the stage, and rode the last 200 km alone.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In the third stage (at a temperature of only 4 degrees Celsius), Faber's chain broke in the last kilometre, and he had to run his bicycle across the finish line.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In the fifth stage, Faber was blown of the road by a strong wind, but remounted.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Later, he was knocked down by a horse that also kicked his bicycle away.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Faber remounted again, and won the stage with a five-minute margin.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In the sixth stage, 20,000 fans had come to see Faber win his fifth stage in a row, which he did.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The 7th stage was won by Ernest Paul, Faber's half brother.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Because of the bad weather, already 50 cyclists (1/3 of the field) had quit the race at that point.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The Tour organisers asked Faber to calm down, in order to keep the Tour exciting.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] His team leader agreed and Faber slowed down and let others win stages; his leading position was never endangered.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In the ninth stage, Faber finished in 10th place at 46 minutes from the winner, his worst performance of the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] He was still leading the race with 26 points, whereas second placed cyclist Garrigou had 40 points.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] It seemed impossible to beat Faber in this Tour, and the question became who would finish in second place.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Gustave Garrigou was in second place, but Jean Alavoine was getting close to him.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Garrigou had more experience, and remained second.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] In the fourteenth stage, Jean Alavoine was leading when his bicycle broke, with only 10 km to go.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Changing bicycles was not allowed, so Alavoine ran the last 10 km with his bicycle on his shoulders, and still won the stage with a margin of 6 minutes and 30 seconds.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The Alcyon-sponsored cyclists dominated the 1909 Tour de France, winning 13 out of 14 stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Only the 7th stage was not won by a cyclist sponsored by Alcyon, but by Ernest Paul, without sponsor.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] After the eighth stage, when only 71 cyclists were still in the race, the points given in the first eight stages were redistributed among the remaining cyclists, in accordance with their positions in those stages.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Of the 150 starting cyclists, 55 finished.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] François Faber is one of the youngest Tour de France winners in history at only 22 years and 7 months; as of 2019, only Henri Cornet in 1904 was younger (19 years and 11 months).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] Sixth-placed Ernest Paul became the winner of the "isolé" category.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1909-tour-de-france] The organising newspaper l'Auto named François Faber the *meilleur grimpeur*.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The **1968 Tour de France** was the 55th edition of the Tour de France, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] It took place between 27 June and 21 July, with 22 stages covering a distance of 4,492 km (2,791 mi).
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Eleven national teams of 10 riders competed, with three French teams, two Belgian teams and one from Germany, Spain, the United Kingdom, Italy, the Netherlands, and a combined Swiss/Luxembourgian team.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The 1968 Tour marked the first time the race would end at the Vélodrome de Vincennes, replacing the now-defunct Parc des Princes Velodrome which served as the final stop from 1904 to 1967.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The general classification was won by Jan Janssen, who overtook Herman Van Springel in the final time trial.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] After the death of Tom Simpson, doping controls had become mandatory.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] To further protect the cyclists, it was now allowed to get water during the race, and two rest days were added.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] To get more sponsor income, a new classification was added, the combination classification, calculated from the positions in the general, points and mountains classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The jersey of the points classification, which has been green in all other years, was red in 1968 for sponsorship reasons.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The 1968 Tour started with 110 cyclists, divided into 11 teams of 10 cyclists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The route for the Tour de France was announced in December 1967.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] At that time, the last stage was not finalised yet, because the old finish place (the Parc des Princes) was no longer available, and a new one had to be found.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The 1968 Tour de France started on 27 June, and had two rest days, in Royan and Font-Romeu-Odeillo-Via.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was 2,408 m (7,900 ft) at the summit of the Port d'Envalira mountain pass on stage 13.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The initial time trial was won by Charly Grosskost, with most favourites shortly behind him.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Grosskost also won the next stage, and thus kept the lead.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the first part of the third stage, a team time trial, the Belgian A team won, and because of the time bonuses Herman Vanspringel took over the lead.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The next stages were all flat, and the favourites were unable to gain time on each other.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the fourth stage, a group without favourites escaped and won the stage with a margin of a few minutes; Jean-Pierre Genet was the best-placed cyclist of that group, and became the new leader.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] A similar thing happened in the first part of the fifth stage; Georges Vandenberghe was the only cyclist who had been present in both escape groups, and he became the new leader of the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Vandenberghe was now a few minutes ahead in the general classification, and kept that lead until the start of the Pyrenees after stage eleven.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Vandenberghe was expected to lose the lead in the twelfth stage, because he was not known to be a good climber.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] But he surprised, and stayed with some of the favourites, keeping the lead.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In that stage, the Dutch team was reduced to four cyclists, and the leader Jan Janssen did not look strong.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] On the other hand, the leader of the French team Raymond Poulidor had gained time, and seemed to be the best-placed favourite, in fifth place in the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the thirteenth stage, Vandenberghe again was able to stay at the front.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the last day in the Pyrenees during stage fourteen, Janssen won the stage, but won little time by that, as almost all cyclists were in the group just behind him.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the fifteenth stage, Raymond Poulidor was hit by a motor, but was able to remount and reach the finish, although he lost more than a minute on his direct competitors.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the sixteenth stage, French internal rivalry was dominating; while Roger Pingeon of the France A team was slowing down to drink, Lucien Aimar of the France B team attacked, and took a group of favourites with him.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Although Aimar was later dropped from that group, Godefroot, Janssen, Vanspringel, Bracke and Gandarias stayed at the front, while Pingeon, Poulidor and Vandenberghe lost more than nine minutes, and were out of contention.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The new leader was now Rolf Wolfshohl, with San Miguel in second place and Franco Bitossi in third place.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the eighteenth stage, Pingeon fought back and escaped early in the stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] He was joined by Bitossi, who was keen on taking over the lead in the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] On the last climb, Bitossi was out of energy and lost considerable time.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Pingeon won the stage, and San Miguel climbed up to the first place in the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] However, the top eight was within two minutes of each other.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the nineteenth stage, San Miguel lost a little time on Vanspringel, who became the new leader.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The next few stages did not change anything in the top of the general classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The Tour ended with a time trial, and before the time trial, Herman Van Springel was leading, followed by San Miguel at 12 seconds, Janssen at 16 seconds and Bitossi at 58 seconds.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Janssen won the final time trial, with Van Springel in second place, but the margin was large enough for Janssen to win the Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Doping controls were performed daily on the first three riders to complete the stage and three more riders by random drawing.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Gimondi advised the Tour de France organizers adopt the aforementioned system, which was used at the Giro d'Italia earlier that year, in order for him to agree to participate in the race.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In total, 163 doping tests were performed.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Both were removed from the race, suspended for one month and given a fine.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] There were several classifications in the 1968 Tour de France, two of them awarding jerseys to their leaders.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The most important was the general classification, calculated by adding each cyclist's finishing times on each stage.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey; the winner of this classification is considered the winner of the Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Additionally, there was a points classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In the points classification, cyclists got points for finishing among the best in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points lead the classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The jersey for the points classification leader was red in 1968, unlike all other years since its introduction in 1953, when it was green.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] There was also a mountains classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The organisation had categorised some climbs as either first, second, third, or fourth-category; points for this classification were won by the first cyclists that reached the top of these climbs first, with more points available for the higher-categorised climbs.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The leader of the mountains classification, which had been calculated since 1933 but had never had a jersey, also became identifiable by a "macaron" on his jersey.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] A newly introduced classification was the combination classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] This classification was calculated as a combination of the other classifications.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The leader was not identified by a jersey, but wore a "macaron" on their jersey.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The fifth individual classification was the intermediate sprints classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] This classification had similar rules as the points classification, but points were only awarded on intermediate sprints.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In 1968, this classification had no associated jersey.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] For the team classification, the times of the best three cyclists per team on each stage were added; the leading team was the team with the lowest total time.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that led this classification wore yellow caps.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The Switzerland/Luxembourg team finished with only two cyclists.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] In addition, there was a combativity award given after each stage to the cyclist considered most combative.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The split stages each had a combined winner.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The decision was made by a jury composed of journalists who gave points.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points from votes in all stages led the combativity classification.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] Roger Pingeon won this classification, and was given overall the super-combativity award.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] The Souvenir Henri Desgrange was given in honour of Tour founder Henri Desgrange to the first rider to pass the summit of the Col des Aravis on stage 19.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] There was also the Souvenir Tom Simpson, given in honour of Tom Simpson, who died during the 1967 Tour.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] This prize was won by Roger Pingeon on stage 15 in the small town of Mirepoix.
[src:1968-tour-de-france/1968-tour-de-france] It was the last edition in which the cyclists participated in national teams; from 1969 on, commercial teams were used.
